Parts and Labour is interesting but flawed. Part of it is that there's a lot of unnecessary detail and repitition, but there's also poor word choice or sentence structure in some places that ends up being distracting. I'm gonna just give two quick examples of what I mean.
>Trepidatiously, Nate turned in and parked, hopefully between two of the faded lines painted on the parking lot’s blacktop. As he stepped out of his car, he was hit by a wave of summer heat and squinted in the intense sunlight. As his eyes normalized, his attention was drawn to some movement in one of the nearby open bay doors. In the dim interior, he could see that there was a white car lifted into the air atop a metal pillar, from underneath which, stepped a short rodent girl.
Trepidatiously works, but honestly this first sentence would fit better at the end of the last paragraph. Second line doesn't sound right when read out loud, I think its the combination of 'was hit by' and 'squinted in.' It juxtaposes passive and active voice. Third sentence can be shortened, normalized is an awkward choice. Fourth has too much important information and should be split into two sentences.
>Stepping out of his car, Nate's senses were quickly overwhelmed by both the blinding sunlight and the scorching summer heat. As his eyes adjusted, his attention was drawn to movement in the nearby doorway. Peering inside the dim interior, he saw a white car suspended in the air from atop a steel pillar.
